[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Modern scripting languages include PHP, Python, Ruby and Lua.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] (Lua is widely used in game development.) All of these have interpreter and compiler support.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] "When the field of compiling began in the late 50s, its focus was limited to the translation of high-level language programs into machine code ...
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The compiler field is increasingly intertwined with other disciplines including computer architecture, programming languages, formal methods, software engineering, and computer security." The "Compiler Research: The Next 50 Years" article noted the importance of object-oriented languages and Java.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Security and parallel computing were cited among the future research targets.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] A compiler implements a formal transformation from a high-level source program to a low-level target program.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Compiler design can define an end-to-end solution or tackle a defined subset that interfaces with other compiling tools e.g., preprocessors, assemblers, linkers.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Design requirements include rigorously defined interfaces both internally between compiler components and externally between supporting toolsets.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] In the early days, the approach taken to compiler design was directly affected by the complexity of the computer language to be processed, the experience of the person(s) designing it, and the resources available.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Resource limitations led to the need to pass through the source code more than once.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] A compiler for a relatively simple language written by one person might be a single, monolithic piece of software.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] However, as the source language grows in complexity the design may be split into a number of interdependent phases.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Separate phases provide design improvements that focus development on the functions in the compiling process.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Classifying compilers by number of passes has its background in the hardware resource limitations of computers.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Compiling involves performing much work and early computers did not have enough memory to contain one program that did all of this work.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] As a result, compilers were split up into smaller programs which each made a pass over the source (or some representation of it) performing some of the required analysis and translations.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The ability to compile in a single pass has classically been seen as a benefit because it simplifies the job of writing a compiler and one-pass compilers generally compile source code faster than multi-pass compilers.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Thus, partly driven by the resource limits of early systems, many early languages were specifically designed so that they could be compiled in one pass (e.g., Pascal).
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] In some cases, the design of a language feature may require a compiler to perform more than one pass over the source.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] For example, consider a declaration appearing on line 20 of the source which affects the translation of a statement appearing on line 10.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] In this case, the first pass needs to gather information about declarations appearing after statements that they affect, with the translation then performed during a subsequent pass.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The disadvantage of compiling in a single pass is that it is not possible to perform many of the sophisticated optimizations needed to generate high quality code.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] It can be difficult to count exactly how many passes an optimizing compiler makes.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] For instance, different phases of optimization may analyse one expression many times but only analyse another expression once.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Splitting a compiler up into small programs is a technique used by researchers interested in producing provably correct compilers.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Proving the correctness of a set of small programs often requires less effort than proving the correctness of a larger, single, equivalent program.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Regardless of the exact number of phases in the compiler design, the phases can be assigned to one of three stages.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The stages include a front end, a middle end, and a back end.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] This front/middle/back-end approach makes it possible to combine front ends for different languages with back ends for different CPUs while sharing the optimizations of the middle end.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Practical examples of this approach are the GNU Compiler Collection, Clang (LLVM-based C/C++ compiler), and the Amsterdam Compiler Kit, which have multiple front-ends, shared optimizations and multiple back-ends.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The front end analyzes the source code to build an internal representation of the program, called the intermediate representation (IR).
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] It also manages the symbol table, a data structure mapping each symbol in the source code to associated information such as location, type and scope.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] While the frontend can be a single monolithic function or program, as in a scannerless parser, it was traditionally implemented and analyzed as several phases, which may execute sequentially or concurrently.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] This method is favored due to its modularity and separation of concerns.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Most commonly, the frontend is broken into three phases: lexical analysis (also known as lexing or scanning), syntax analysis (also known as scanning or parsing), and semantic analysis.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Lexing and parsing comprise the syntactic analysis (word syntax and phrase syntax, respectively), and in simple cases, these modules (the lexer and parser) can be automatically generated from a grammar for the language, though in more complex cases these require manual modification.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The lexical grammar and phrase grammar are usually context-free grammars, which simplifies analysis significantly, with context-sensitivity handled at the semantic analysis phase.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The semantic analysis phase is generally more complex and written by hand, but can be partially or fully automated using attribute grammars.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] These phases themselves can be further broken down: lexing as scanning and evaluating, and parsing as building a concrete syntax tree (CST, parse tree) and then transforming it into an abstract syntax tree (AST, syntax tree).
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] In some cases additional phases are used, notably *line reconstruction* and *preprocessing,* but these are rare.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The middle end, also known as *optimizer,* performs optimizations on the intermediate representation in order to improve the performance and the quality of the produced machine code.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The middle end contains those optimizations that are independent of the CPU architecture being targeted.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Compiler analysis is the prerequisite for any compiler optimization, and they tightly work together.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] For example, dependence analysis is crucial for loop transformation.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The scope of compiler analysis and optimizations vary greatly; their scope may range from operating within a basic block, to whole procedures, or even the whole program.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] There is a trade-off between the granularity of the optimizations and the cost of compilation.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] For example, peephole optimizations are fast to perform during compilation but only affect a small local fragment of the code, and can be performed independently of the context in which the code fragment appears.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] In contrast, interprocedural optimization requires more compilation time and memory space, but enable optimizations that are only possible by considering the behavior of multiple functions simultaneously.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Interprocedural analysis and optimizations are common in modern commercial compilers from HP, IBM, SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The free software GCC was criticized for a long time for lacking powerful interprocedural optimizations, but it is changing in this respect.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Another open source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64, which is used by many organizations for research and commercial purposes.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Due to the extra time and space needed for compiler analysis and optimizations, some compilers skip them by default.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Users have to use compilation options to explicitly tell the compiler which optimizations should be enabled.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The back end is responsible for the CPU architecture specific optimizations and for code generation.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Compiler correctness is the branch of software engineering that deals with trying to show that a compiler behaves according to its language specification.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Techniques include developing the compiler using formal methods and using rigorous testing (often called compiler validation) on an existing compiler.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Higher-level programming languages usually appear with a type of translation in mind: either designed as compiled language or interpreted language.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] However, in practice there is rarely anything about a language that *requires* it to be exclusively compiled or exclusively interpreted, although it is possible to design languages that rely on re-interpretation at run time.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The categorization usually reflects the most popular or widespread implementations of a language.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] For instance, BASIC is sometimes called an interpreted language, and C a compiled one, despite the existence of BASIC compilers and C interpreters.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Interpretation does not replace compilation completely.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] It only hides it from the user and makes it gradual.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Even though an interpreter can itself be interpreted, a set of directly executed machine instructions is needed somewhere at the bottom of the execution stack (see machine language).
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Furthermore, for optimization compilers can contain interpreter functionality, and interpreters may include ahead of time compilation techniques.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] For example, where an expression can be executed during compilation and the results inserted into the output program, then it prevents it having to be recalculated each time the program runs, which can greatly speed up the final program.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Modern trends toward just-in-time compilation and bytecode interpretation at times blur the traditional categorizations of compilers and interpreters even further.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Meta-tracing is an automated compiler synthesis approach which takes this further and can be used to synthesize a compiler from a language interpreter.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Some language specifications spell out that implementations *must* include a compilation facility; for example, Common Lisp.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] However, there is nothing inherent in the definition of Common Lisp that stops it from being interpreted.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] To implement these features in a compiled language, programs must usually be shipped with a runtime library that includes a version of the compiler itself.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] One classification of compilers is by the platform on which their generated code executes.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] A *native* or *hosted* compiler is one whose output is intended to directly run on the same type of computer and operating system that the compiler itself runs on.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The output of a cross compiler is designed to run on a different platform.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Cross compilers are often used when developing software for embedded systems that are not intended to support a software development environment.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The output of a compiler that produces code for a virtual machine (VM) may or may not be executed on the same platform as the compiler that produced it.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] For this reason, such compilers are not usually classified as native or cross compilers.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The lower level language that is the target of a compiler may itself be a high-level programming language.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] C, viewed by some as a sort of portable assembly language, is frequently the target language of such compilers.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] For example, Cfront, the original compiler for C++, used C as its target language.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] The C code generated by such a compiler is usually not intended to be readable and maintained by humans, so indent style and creating pretty C intermediate code are ignored.
[src:gambit-scheme/compiler] Some of the features of C that make it a good target language include the `#line` directive, which can be generated by the compiler to support debugging of the original source, and the wide platform support available with C compilers.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] In computer science, a **continuation** is an abstract representation of the control state of a computer program.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Continuations are useful for encoding other control mechanisms in programming languages such as exceptions, generators, coroutines, and so on.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] The "**current continuation**" or "continuation of the computation step" is the continuation that, from the perspective of running code, would be derived from the current point in a program's execution.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] The term *continuations* can also be used to refer to **first-class continuations**, which are constructs that give a programming language the ability to save the execution state at any point and return to that point at a later point in the program, possibly multiple times.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] The earliest description of continuations was made by Adriaan van Wijngaarden in September 1964.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Wijngaarden spoke at the IFIP Working Conference on Formal Language Description Languages held in Baden bei Wien, Austria.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] As part of a formulation for an Algol 60 preprocessor, he called for a transformation of proper procedures into continuation-passing style, though he did not use this name, and his intention was to simplify a program and thus make its result more clear.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Reynolds brought the term *continuation* into prominence in their work in the field of denotational semantics that makes extensive use of continuations to allow sequential programs to be analysed in terms of functional programming semantics.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Steve Russell invented the continuation in his second Lisp implementation for the IBM 704, though he did not name it.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Reynolds (1993) gives a complete history of the discovery of continuations.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] First-class continuations are a language's ability to completely control the execution order of instructions.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] They can be used to jump to a function that produced the call to the current function, or to a function that has previously exited.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] One can think of a first-class continuation as saving the *execution* state of the program.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] True first-class continuations do not save program data – unlike a process image – only the execution context.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Scheme was the first full production system providing first "catch" and then call/cc.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Continuations are also used in models of computation including denotational semantics, the actor model, process calculi, and lambda calculus.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] These models rely on programmers or semantics engineers to write mathematical functions in the so-called continuation-passing style.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] This means that each function consumes a function that represents the rest of the computation relative to this function call.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] To return a value, the function calls this "continuation function" with a return value; to abort the computation it returns a value.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Functional programmers who write their programs in continuation-passing style gain the expressive power to manipulate the flow of control in arbitrary ways.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] The cost is that they must maintain the invariants of control and continuations by hand, which can be a highly complex undertaking (but see 'continuation-passing style' below).
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Continuations simplify and clarify the implementation of several common design patterns, including coroutines/green threads and exception handling, by providing the basic, low-level primitive which unifies these seemingly unconnected patterns.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Continuations can provide elegant solutions to some difficult high-level problems, like programming a web server that supports multiple pages, accessed by the use of the forward and back buttons and by following links.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] The Smalltalk Seaside web framework uses continuations to great effect, allowing one to program the web server in procedural style, by switching continuations when switching pages.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] More complex constructs for which *"continuations provide an elegant description"* also exist.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] For example, in C, longjmp can be used to jump from the middle of one function to another, provided the second function lies deeper in the stack (if it is waiting for the first function to return, possibly among others).
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Other more complex examples include coroutines in Simula 67, Lua, and Perl; tasklets in Stackless Python; generators in Icon and Python; continuations in Scala (starting in 2.8); fibers in Ruby (starting in 1.9.1); the backtracking mechanism in Prolog; monads in functional programming; and threads.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] For a gentler introduction to this mechanism, see call-with-current-continuation.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] This example shows a possible usage of continuations to implement coroutines as separate threads.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] A program must allocate space in memory for the variables its functions use.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Most programming languages use a call stack for storing the variables needed because it allows for fast and simple allocating and automatic deallocation of memory.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Other programming languages use a heap for this, which allows for flexibility at a higher cost for allocating and deallocating memory.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Both of these implementations have benefits and drawbacks in the context of continuations.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] In any language which supports closures and proper tail calls, it is possible to write programs in continuation-passing style and manually implement call/cc.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] (In continuation-passing style, call/cc becomes a simple function that can be written with lambda.) This is a particularly common strategy in Haskell, where it is easy to construct a "continuation-passing monad" (for example, the `Cont` monad and `ContT` monad transformer in the `mtl` library).
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] The support for proper tail calls is needed because in continuation-passing style no function ever returns; *all* calls are tail calls.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] One area that has seen practical use of continuations is in Web programming.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] The use of continuations shields the programmer from the stateless nature of the HTTP protocol.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] In the traditional model of web programming, the lack of state is reflected in the program's structure, leading to code constructed around a model that lends itself very poorly to expressing computational problems.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Thus continuations enable code that has the useful properties associated with inversion of control, while avoiding its problems.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] "Inverting back the inversion of control or, Continuations versus page-centric programming" is a paper that provides a good introduction to continuations applied to web programming.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Support for continuations varies widely.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] A programming language supports *re-invocable* continuations if a continuation may be invoked repeatedly (even after it has already returned).
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Re-invocable continuations were introduced by Peter J.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Landin using his **J** (for Jump) operator that could transfer the flow of control back into the middle of a procedure invocation.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Re-invocable continuations have also been called "re-entrant" in the Racket language.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] However this use of the term "re-entrant" can be easily confused with its use in discussions of multithreading.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] A more limited kind is the *escape continuation* that may be used to escape the current context to a surrounding one.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Many languages which do not explicitly support continuations support exception handling, which is equivalent to escape continuations and can be used for the same purposes.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] C's `setjmp/longjmp` are also equivalent: they can only be used to unwind the stack.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Escape continuations can also be used to implement tail call elimination.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] One generalization of continuations are delimited continuations.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Continuation operators like `call/cc` capture the *entire* remaining computation at a given point in the program and provide no way of delimiting this capture.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Delimited continuation operators address this by providing two separate control mechanisms: a *prompt* that delimits a continuation operation and a *reification* operator such as `shift` or `control`.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Continuations captured using delimited operators thus only represent a slice of the program context.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] Continuations are the functional expression of the GOTO statement, and the same caveats apply.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] While they are a sensible option in some special cases such as web programming, use of continuations can result in code that is difficult to follow.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] In fact, the esoteric programming language Unlambda includes call-with-current-continuation as one of its features solely because expressions involving it "tend to be hopelessly difficult to track down".
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] The external links below illustrate the concept in more detail.
[src:gambit-scheme/continuation] The extent to which continuations can be used to explain other general phenomena in natural language is a topic of current research.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] They have been described as "functions whose execution you can pause".
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Melvin Conway coined the term *coroutine* in 1958 when he applied it to the construction of an assembly program.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] The first published explanation of the coroutine appeared later, in 1963.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] There is no single precise definition of coroutine.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] 2. the execution of a coroutine is suspended as control leaves it, only to carry on where it left off when control re-enters the coroutine at some later stage.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] 3. whether a coroutine is able to suspend its execution from within nested function calls.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Such a coroutine is a *stackful coroutine*.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] One to the contrary is called *stackless coroutines*, where unless marked as coroutine, a regular function can't use the keyword `yield`.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] The paper "Revisiting Coroutines" published in 2009 proposed the term *full coroutine* to denote one that supports first-class coroutine and is stackful.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Full Coroutines deserve their own name in that they have the same expressive power as one-shot continuations and delimited continuations.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Full coroutines are either symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Importantly, whether a coroutine is symmetric or asymmetric has no bearing on how expressive it can be, though full coroutines are more expressive than non-full coroutines.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] While their expressive power is the same, asymmetrical coroutines more closely resemble routine based control structures in the sense that control is always passed back to the invoker, which programmers may find more familiar.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Subroutines are special cases of coroutines.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] When subroutines are invoked, execution begins at the start, and once a subroutine exits, it is finished; an instance of a subroutine only returns once, and does not hold state between invocations.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] By contrast, coroutines can exit by calling other coroutines, which may later return to the point where they were invoked in the original coroutine; from the coroutine's point of view, it is not exiting but calling another coroutine.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Thus, a coroutine instance holds state, and varies between invocations; there can be multiple instances of a given coroutine at once.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] The difference between calling another coroutine by means of "yielding" to it and simply calling another routine (which then, also, would return to the original point), is that the relationship between two coroutines which yield to each other is not that of caller-callee, but instead symmetric.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Any subroutine can be translated to a coroutine which does not call *yield*.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Here is a simple example of how coroutines can be useful.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Suppose you have a consumer-producer relationship where one routine creates items and adds them to a queue and another removes items from the queue and uses them.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] For reasons of efficiency, you want to add and remove several items at once.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] The queue is then completely filled or emptied before yielding control to the other coroutine using the *yield* command.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] The further coroutines calls are starting right after the *yield*, in the outer coroutine loop.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Although this example is often used as an introduction to multithreading, two threads are not needed for this: the *yield* statement can be implemented by a jump directly from one routine into the other.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] However, coroutines are cooperatively multitasked, whereas threads are typically preemptively multitasked.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Coroutines provide concurrency, because they allow tasks to be performed out of order or in a changeable order, without changing the overall outcome, but they do not provide parallelism, because they do not execute multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] It is possible to implement coroutines using preemptively-scheduled threads, in a way that will be transparent to the calling code, but some of the advantages (particularly the suitability for hard-realtime operation and relative cheapness of switching between them) will be lost.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a subset of coroutines.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] That is, since generators are primarily used to simplify the writing of iterators, the `yield` statement in a generator does not specify a coroutine to jump to, but rather passes a value back to a parent routine.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] A number of implementations of coroutines for languages with generator support but no native coroutines (e.g.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Python before 2.5) use this or a similar model.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Using coroutines for state machines or concurrency is similar to using mutual recursion with tail calls, as in both cases the control changes to a different one of a set of routines.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] However, coroutines are more flexible and generally more efficient.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Further, each mutually recursive call of a subroutine requires a new stack frame (unless tail call elimination is implemented), while passing control between coroutines uses the existing contexts and can be implemented simply by a jump.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Coroutines originated as an assembly language method, but are supported in some high-level programming languages.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Java does not have native or library support for coroutines, but it can call Kotlin coroutines `kotlinx.coroutines` (though this is not ideal and would require a Java wrapper over Kotlin).
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Since continuations can be used to implement coroutines, programming languages that support them can also quite easily support coroutines.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] As of 2003, many of the most popular programming languages, including C and its derivatives, do not have built-in support for coroutines within the language or their standard libraries.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] This is, in large part, due to the limitations of stack-based subroutine implementation.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] An exception is the C++ library Boost.Context, part of Boost, which supports context swapping on ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, SPARC and x86 on POSIX, Mac OS X and Windows.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Coroutines can be built upon Boost.Context.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Conditionals within the code result in the execution of different code paths on successive calls, based on the values of the state variables.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Another typical response is to implement an explicit state machine in the form of a large and complex switch statement or via a goto statement, particularly a computed goto.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Such implementations are considered difficult to understand and maintain, and a motivation for coroutine support.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Threads, and to a lesser extent fibers, are an alternative to coroutines in mainstream programming environments today.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Threads provide facilities for managing the real-time cooperative interaction of *simultaneously* executing pieces of code.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Threads are widely available in environments that support C (and are supported natively in many other modern languages), are familiar to many programmers, and are usually well-implemented, well-documented and well-supported.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] However, as they solve a large and difficult problem they include many powerful and complex facilities and have a correspondingly difficult learning curve.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] As such, when a coroutine is all that is needed, using a thread can be overkill.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] One important difference between threads and coroutines is that threads are typically preemptively scheduled while coroutines are not.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Because threads can be rescheduled at any instant and can execute concurrently, programs using threads must be careful about locking.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] In contrast, because coroutines can only be rescheduled at specific points in the program and do not execute concurrently, programs using coroutines can often avoid locking entirely.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] This property is also cited as a benefit of event-driven or asynchronous programming.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Since fibers are cooperatively scheduled, they provide an ideal base for implementing coroutines above.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] However, system support for fibers is often lacking compared to that for threads.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] In order to implement general-purpose coroutines, a second call stack must be obtained, which is a feature not directly supported by the C language.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] A reliable (albeit platform-specific) way to achieve this is to use a small amount of inline assembly to explicitly manipulate the stack pointer during initial creation of the coroutine.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] This is the approach recommended by Tom Duff in a discussion on its relative merits vs. the method used by Protothreads.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] On platforms which provide the POSIX sigaltstack system call, a second call stack can be obtained by calling a springboard function from within a signal handler to achieve the same goal in portable C, at the cost of some extra complexity.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] C libraries complying to POSIX or the Single Unix Specification (SUSv3) provided such routines as getcontext, setcontext, makecontext and swapcontext, but these functions were declared obsolete in POSIX 1.2008.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Once a second call stack has been obtained with one of the methods listed above, the setjmp and longjmp functions in the standard C library can then be used to implement the switches between coroutines.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] These functions save and restore, respectively, the stack pointer, program counter, callee-saved registers, and any other internal state as required by the ABI, such that returning to a coroutine after having yielded restores all the state that would be restored upon returning from a function call.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Minimalist implementations, which do not piggyback off the setjmp and longjmp functions, may achieve the same result via a small block of inline assembly which swaps merely the stack pointer and program counter, and clobbers all other registers.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] This can be significantly faster, as setjmp and longjmp must conservatively store all registers which may be in use according to the ABI, whereas the clobber method allows the compiler to store (by spilling to the stack) only what it knows is actually in use.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Due to the lack of direct language support, many authors have written their own libraries for coroutines which hide the above details.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Russ Cox's libtask library is a good example of this genre.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] It uses the context functions if they are provided by the native C library; otherwise it provides its own implementations for ARM, PowerPC, Sparc, and x86.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Other notable implementations include libpcl, coro, lthread, libCoroutine, libconcurrency, libcoro, ribs2, libdill., libaco, and libco.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] In addition to the general approach above, several attempts have been made to approximate coroutines in C with combinations of subroutines and macros.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Simon Tatham's contribution, based on Duff's device, is a notable example of the genre, and is the basis for Protothreads and similar implementations.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] C++20 introduced standardized coroutines as stackless functions that can be suspended in the middle of execution and resumed at a later point.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] The suspended state of a coroutine is stored on the heap.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Implementation of this standard is ongoing, with the G++ and MSVC compilers currently fully supporting standard coroutines in recent versions.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] A generator class for synchronous and lazy-evaluated ranges, `std::generator`, was added in C++23.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] It is invoked using `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] This is an example of C++20 coroutines with the C++26 `std::execution::task` class.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] C# 2.0 added semi-coroutine (generator) functionality through the iterator pattern and `yield` keyword.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Cloroutine is a third-party library providing support for stackless coroutines in Clojure.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] It's implemented as a macro, statically splitting an arbitrary code block on arbitrary var calls and emitting the coroutine as a stateful function.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] D implements coroutines as its standard library class `core.thread.Fiber` for a fiber.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] A generator (`std.concurrency.Generator`) makes it trivial to expose a fiber function as an input range (`std.range.interfaces.InputRange`), making any fiber compatible with existing range algorithms.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Go has a built-in concept of "goroutines", a type of green thread which are lightweight, independent processes managed by the Go runtime.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] A new goroutine can be started using the "go" keyword.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Each goroutine has a variable-size stack which can be expanded as needed.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Goroutines generally communicate using Go's built-in channels.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] However, goroutines are not coroutines (for instance, local data does not persist between successive calls).
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] There are several implementations for coroutines in Java.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Despite the constraints imposed by Java's abstractions, the JVM does not preclude the possibility.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] There are four general methods used, but two break bytecode portability among standards-compliant JVMs.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Since ECMAScript 2015, JavaScript has support for generators, which are a special case of coroutines.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Kotlin implements coroutines as part of a first-party library.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Lua has supported first-class stackful asymmetric coroutines since version 5.0 (2003), in the standard library *coroutine*.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Modula-2 as defined by Wirth implements coroutines as part of the standard SYSTEM library.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] The procedure NEWPROCESS() fills in a context given a code block and space for a stack as parameters, and the procedure TRANSFER() transfers control to a coroutine given the coroutine's context as its parameter.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] The Mono Common Language Runtime has support for continuations, from which coroutines can be built.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] During the development of the .NET Framework 2.0, Microsoft extended the design of the Common Language Runtime (CLR) hosting APIs to handle fiber-based scheduling with an eye towards its use in fiber-mode for SQL server.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Before release, support for the task switching hook `ICLRTask::SwitchOut` was removed due to time constraints.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Consequently, the use of the fiber API to switch tasks is currently not a viable option in the .NET Framework.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] OCaml supports coroutines through its `Thread` module.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] These coroutines provide concurrency without parallelism, and are scheduled preemptively on a single operating system thread.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Since OCaml 5.0, green threads are also available; provided by different modules.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Coroutines are natively implemented in all Raku backends.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Python has support for coroutines using the `asyncio.create_task()` function.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Racket provides native continuations, with a trivial implementation of coroutines provided in the official package catalog.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Since Scheme provides full support for continuations, implementing coroutines is nearly trivial, requiring only that a queue of continuations be maintained.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Since, in most Smalltalk environments, the execution stack is a first-class citizen, coroutines can be implemented without additional library or VM support.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Since version 8.6, Tcl supports coroutines in the core language.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Vala implements native support for coroutines.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] They are designed to be used with a GTK Main Loop, but can be used alone if care is taken to ensure that the end callback will never have to be called before doing, at least, one yield.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Machine-dependent assembly languages often provide direct methods for coroutine execution.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] On VAXen (in VAX MACRO) the comparable instruction is "JSB @(SP)+".
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] Even on a Motorola 6809 there is the instruction "JSR [,S++]"; note the "++", as 2 bytes (of address) are popped from the stack.
[src:gambit-scheme/coroutine] This instruction is much used in the (standard) 'monitor' Assist 09.
[src:gambit-scheme/gambit-scheme-implementation] By compiling to an intermediate representation, in this case portable C (as do Chicken, Bigloo and Cyclone), programs written in Gambit can be compiled for common popular operating systems such as Linux, macOS, other Unix-like systems, and Windows.
[src:gambit-scheme/gambit-scheme-implementation] Gerbil scheme is a variant of Scheme implemented on Gambit-C.
[src:gambit-scheme/gambit-scheme-implementation] It supports current R*RS standards and common SRFIs and has a state of the art macro and module system inspired by Racket.
[src:gambit-scheme/gambit-scheme-implementation] Termite Scheme is a variant of Scheme implemented on Gambit-C.
[src:gambit-scheme/gambit-scheme-implementation] Termite is intended for distributed computing, it offers a simple and powerful message passing model of concurrency, inspired by that of Erlang.
[src:gambit-scheme/gambit-scheme-implementation] While the Gambit compiler produces C code only, it has full integration support for C++ and Objective-C compilers such as GNU Compiler Collection (GCC).
[src:gambit-scheme/gambit-scheme-implementation] Thus, software written in Gambit-C can contain C++ or Objective-C code, and can fully integrate with corresponding libraries.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The Scheme language is standardized in the official Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) standard and a *de facto* standard named the *Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme* (R*n*RS).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A widely implemented standard is R5RS (1998).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The most recently ratified standard of Scheme is "R7RS-small" (2013).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The more expansive and modular R6RS was ratified in 2007.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Both trace their descent from R5RS; the timeline below reflects the chronological order of ratification.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme started in the 1970s as an attempt to understand Carl Hewitt's Actor model, for which purpose Steele and Sussman wrote a "tiny Lisp interpreter" using Maclisp and then "added mechanisms for creating actors and sending messages".
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme was originally called "Schemer", in the tradition of other Lisp-derived languages such as Planner or *Conniver*.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The current name resulted from the authors' use of the ITS operating system, which limited filenames to two components of at most six characters each.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Currently, "Schemer" is commonly used to refer to a Scheme programmer.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A new language standardization process began at the 2003 Scheme workshop, with the goal of producing an R6RS standard in 2006.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This process broke with the earlier R*n*RS approach of unanimity.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS features a standard module system, allowing a split between the core language and libraries.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Several drafts of the R6RS specification were released, the final version being R5.97RS.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A successful vote resulted in ratifying the new standard, announced on August 28, 2007.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Currently the newest releases of various Scheme implementations support the R6RS standard.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] There is a portable reference implementation of the proposed implicitly phased libraries for R6RS, called psyntax, which loads and bootstraps itself properly on various older Scheme implementations.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A feature of R6RS is the record-type descriptor (RTD).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] When an RTD is created and used, the record type representation can show the memory layout.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] It also calculated object field bit mask and mutable Scheme object field bit masks, and helped the garbage collector know what to do with the fields without traversing the whole fields list that are saved in the RTD.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] RTD allows users to expand the basic RTD to create a new record system.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS introduces numerous significant changes to the language.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The source code is now specified in Unicode, and a large subset of Unicode characters may now appear in Scheme symbols and identifiers, and there are other minor changes to the lexical rules.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Character data is also now specified in Unicode.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Many standard procedures have been moved to the new standard libraries, which themselves form a large expansion of the standard, containing procedures and syntactic forms that were formerly not part of the standard.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A new module system has been introduced, and systems for exception handling are now standardized.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Syntax-rules has been replaced with a more expressive syntactic abstraction facility (syntax-case) which allows the use of all of Scheme at macro expansion time.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Compliant implementations are now *required* to support Scheme's full numeric tower, and the semantics of numbers have been expanded, mainly in the direction of support for the IEEE 754 standard for floating point numerical representation.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard has caused controversy because some see it as a departure from the minimalist philosophy.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Two working groups were created to work on these two new versions of Scheme.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The Scheme Reports Process site has links to the working groups' charters, public discussions and issue tracking system.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The ninth draft of R7RS (small language) was made available on April 15, 2013.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A vote ratifying this draft closed on May 20, 2013, and the final report has been available since August 6, 2013, describing "the 'small' language of that effort: therefore it cannot be considered in isolation as the successor to R6RS".
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is primarily a functional programming language.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] It shares many characteristics with other members of the Lisp programming language family.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme's very simple syntax is based on s-expressions, parenthesized lists in which a prefix operator is followed by its arguments.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme programs thus consist of sequences of nested lists.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Lists are also the main data structure in Scheme, leading to a close equivalence between source code and data formats (homoiconicity).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme programs can easily create and evaluate pieces of Scheme code dynamically.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The reliance on lists as data structures is shared by all Lisp dialects.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme inherits a rich set of list-processing primitives such as `cons`, `car` and `cdr` from its Lisp progenitors.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme uses strictly but dynamically typed variables and supports first class procedures.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Thus, procedures can be assigned as values to variables or passed as arguments to procedures.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This section concentrates mainly on innovative features of the language, including those features that distinguish Scheme from other Lisps.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Unless stated otherwise, descriptions of features relate to the R5RS standard.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In examples provided in this section, the notation "===> result" is used to indicate the result of evaluating the expression on the immediately preceding line.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This is the same convention used in R5RS.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is a very simple language, much easier to implement than many other languages of comparable expressive power.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This ease is attributable to the use of lambda calculus to derive much of the syntax of the language from more primitive forms.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For instance of the 23 s-expression-based syntactic constructs defined in the R5RS Scheme standard, 14 are classed as derived or library forms, which can be written as macros involving more fundamental forms, principally lambda.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] : define, lambda, quote, if, define-syntax, let-syntax, letrec-syntax, syntax-rules, set!
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example: a macro to implement `let` as an expression using `lambda` to perform the variable bindings.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Thus using `let` as defined above a Scheme implementation would rewrite "`(let ((a 1)(b 2)) (+ b a))`" as "`((lambda (a b) (+ b a)) 1 2)`", which reduces implementation's task to that of coding procedure instantiations.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In 1998, Sussman and Steele remarked that the minimalism of Scheme was not a conscious design goal, but rather the unintended outcome of the design process.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Like most modern programming languages and unlike earlier Lisps such as Maclisp, Scheme is lexically scoped: all possible variable bindings in a program unit can be analyzed by reading the text of the program unit without considering the contexts in which it may be called.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This contrasts with dynamic scoping which was characteristic of early Lisp dialects, because of the processing costs associated with the primitive textual substitution methods used to implement lexical scoping algorithms in compilers and interpreters of the day.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In those Lisps, it was fully possible for a reference to a free variable inside a procedure to refer to quite distinct bindings external to the procedure, depending on the context of the call.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The impetus to incorporate lexical scoping, which was an unusual scoping model in the early 1970s, into their new version of Lisp, came from Sussman's studies of ALGOL.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] He suggested that ALGOL-like lexical scoping mechanisms would help to realize their initial goal of implementing Carl Hewitt's Actor model in Lisp.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Alonzo Church's mathematical notation, the lambda calculus, has inspired Lisp's use of "lambda" as a keyword for introducing a procedure, as well as influencing the development of functional programming techniques involving the use of higher-order functions in Lisp.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] But early Lisps were not suitable expressions of the lambda calculus because of their treatment of free variables.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A formal lambda system has axioms and a complete calculation rule.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] It is helpful for the analysis using mathematical logic and tools.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In this system, calculation can be seen as a directional deduction.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The syntax of lambda calculus follows the recursive expressions from x, y, z, ...,parentheses, spaces, the period and the symbol λ.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The function of lambda calculation includes: First, serve as a starting point of powerful mathematical logic.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Second, it can reduce the requirement of programmers to consider the implementation details, because it can be used to imitate machine evaluation.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Finally, the lambda calculation created a substantial meta-theory.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The introduction of lexical scope resolved the problem by making an equivalence between some forms of lambda notation and their practical expression in a working programming language.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] They introduced continuation-passing style along with their first description of Scheme in the first of the Lambda Papers, and in subsequent papers, they proceeded to demonstrate the raw power of this practical use of lambda calculus.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme inherits its block structure from earlier block structured languages, particularly ALGOL.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, blocks are implemented by three *binding constructs*: `let`, `let*` and `letrec`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Blocks can be nested to create arbitrarily complex block structures according to the need of the programmer.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The use of block structuring to create local bindings alleviates the risk of namespace collision that can otherwise occur.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The other variant, `letrec`, is designed to enable mutually recursive procedures to be bound to one another.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] All procedures bound in a single `letrec` may refer to one another by name, as well as to values of variables defined earlier in the same `letrec`, but they may not refer to *values* defined later in the same `letrec`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A variant of `let`, the "named let" form, has an identifier after the `let` keyword.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This binds the let variables to the argument of a procedure whose name is the given identifier and whose body is the body of the let form.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The body may be repeated as desired by calling the procedure.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The named let is widely used to implement iteration.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Like any procedure in Scheme, the procedure created in the named let is a first-class object.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme has an iteration construct, `do`, but it is more idiomatic in Scheme to use tail recursion to express iteration.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Standard-conforming Scheme implementations are required to optimize tail calls so as to support an unbounded number of active tail calls (R5RS sec.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] 3.5)—a property the Scheme report describes as *proper tail recursion*—making it safe for Scheme programmers to write iterative algorithms using recursive structures, which are sometimes more intuitive.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Tail recursive procedures and the *named `let`* form provide support for iteration using tail recursion.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Continuations in Scheme are first-class objects.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme provides the procedure `call-with-current-continuation` (also known as `call/cc`) to capture the current continuation by packing it up as an escape procedure bound to a formal argument in a procedure provided by the programmer.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] 6.4) First-class continuations enable the programmer to create non-local control constructs such as iterators, coroutines, and backtracking.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Continuations can be used to emulate the behavior of return statements in imperative programming languages.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following function `find-first`, given function `func` and list `lst`, returns the first element `x` in `lst` such that `(func x)` returns true.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following example, a traditional programmer's puzzle, shows that Scheme can handle continuations as first-class objects, binding them to variables and passing them as arguments to procedures.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In contrast to Common Lisp, all data and procedures in Scheme share a common namespace, whereas in Common Lisp functions and data have separate namespaces making it possible for a function and a variable to have the same name, and requiring special notation for referring to a function as a value.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This is sometimes known as the "Lisp-1 vs.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Lisp-2" distinction, referring to the unified namespace of Scheme and the separate namespaces of Common Lisp.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, the same primitives that are used to manipulate and bind data can be used to bind procedures.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] There is no equivalent of Common Lisp's `defun` and `#'` primitives.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This subsection documents design decisions that have been taken over the years which have given Scheme a particular character, but are not the direct outcomes of the original design.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme specifies a comparatively full set of numerical datatypes including complex and rational types, which is known in Scheme as the numerical tower (R5RS sec.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The standard treats these as abstractions, and does not commit the implementor to any particular internal representations.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Numbers may have the quality of exactness.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] An exact number can only be produced by a sequence of exact operations involving other exact numbers—inexactness is thus contagious.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The standard specifies that any two implementations must produce equivalent results for all operations resulting in exact numbers.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R5RS standard specifies procedures `exact->inexact` and `inexact->exact` which can be used to change the exactness of a number.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] `inexact->exact` produces "the exact number that is numerically closest to the argument".
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] `exact->inexact` produces "the inexact number that is numerically closest to the argument".
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard omits these procedures from the main report, but specifies them as R5RS compatibility procedures in the standard library (rnrs r5rs (6)).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In the R5RS standard, Scheme implementations are not required to implement the whole numerical tower, but they must implement "a coherent subset consistent with both the purposes of the implementation and the spirit of the Scheme language" (R5RS sec.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The new R6RS standard does require implementation of the whole tower, and "exact integer objects and exact rational number objects of practically unlimited size and precision, and to implement certain procedures...so they always return exact results when given exact arguments" (R6RS sec.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example 1: exact arithmetic in an implementation that supports exact rational complex numbers.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example 2: Same arithmetic in an implementation that supports neither exact rational numbers nor complex numbers but does accept real numbers in rational notation.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Both implementations conform to the R5RS standard but the second does not conform to R6RS because it does not implement the full numerical tower.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme supports delayed evaluation through the `delay` form and the procedure `force`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The lexical context of the original definition of the promise is preserved, and its value is also preserved after the first use of `force`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The promise is only ever evaluated once.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] These primitives, which produce or handle values known as promises, can be used to implement advanced lazy evaluation constructs such as streams.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In the R6RS standard, these are no longer primitives, but instead, are provided as part of the R5RS compatibility library (rnrs r5rs (6)).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In R5RS, a suggested implementation of `delay` and `force` is given, implementing the promise as a procedure with no arguments (a thunk) and using memoization to ensure that it is only ever evaluated once, irrespective of the number of times `force` is called (R5RS sec.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] SRFI 41 enables the expression of both finite and infinite sequences with extraordinary economy.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most Lisps specify an order of evaluation for procedure arguments.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] ev is a procedure that describes the argument passed to it, then returns the value of the argument.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In contrast with other Lisps, the appearance of an expression in the operator position (the first item) of a Scheme expression is quite legal, as long as the result of the expression in the operator position is a procedure.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In calling the procedure "+" to add 1 and 2, the expressions (ev +), (ev 1) and (ev 2) may be evaluated in any order, as long as the effect is not as if they were evaluated in parallel.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Thus the following three lines may be displayed in any order by standard Scheme when the above example code is executed, although the text of one line may not be interleaved with another because that would violate the sequential evaluation constraint.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In the R5RS standard and in later reports, the syntax of Scheme can easily be extended via the macro system.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R5RS standard introduced a powerful hygienic macro system that allows the programmer to add new syntactic constructs to the language using a simple pattern matching sublanguage (R5RS sec 4.3).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Prior to this, the hygienic macro system had been relegated to an appendix of the R4RS standard, as a "high level" system alongside a "low level" macro system, both of which were treated as extensions to Scheme rather than an essential part of the language.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Implementations of the hygienic macro system, also called `syntax-rules`, are required to respect the lexical scoping of the rest of the language.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This is assured by special naming and scoping rules for macro expansion and avoids common programming errors that can occur in the macro systems of other programming languages.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS specifies a more sophisticated transformation system, `syntax-case`, which has been available as a language extension to R5RS Scheme for some time.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Invocations of macros and procedures bear a close resemblance—both are s-expressions—but they are treated differently.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] When the compiler encounters an s-expression in the program, it first checks to see if the symbol is defined as a syntactic keyword within the current lexical scope.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If so, it then attempts to expand the macro, treating the items in the tail of the s-expression as arguments without compiling code to evaluate them, and this process is repeated recursively until no macro invocations remain.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If it is not a syntactic keyword, the compiler compiles code to evaluate the arguments in the tail of the s-expression and then to evaluate the variable represented by the symbol at the head of the s-expression and call it as a procedure with the evaluated tail expressions passed as arguments to it.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most Scheme implementations also provide additional macro systems.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Among popular ones are syntactic closures, explicit renaming macros and `define-macro`, a non-hygienic macro system similar to `defmacro` system provided in Common Lisp.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The inability to specify whether or not a macro is hygienic is one of the shortcomings of the macro system.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Alternative models for expansion such as scope sets provide a potential solution.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Prior to R5RS, Scheme had no standard equivalent of the `eval` procedure which is ubiquitous in other Lisps, although the first Lambda Paper had described `evaluate` as "similar to the LISP function EVAL" and the first Revised Report in 1978 replaced this with `enclose`, which took two arguments.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The second, third and fourth revised reports omitted any equivalent of `eval`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The reason for this confusion is that in Scheme with its lexical scoping the result of evaluating an expression depends on where it is evaluated.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If it is evaluated in the outer environment, where `name` is defined, the result is the sum of the operands.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] If it is evaluated in the inner environment, where the symbol "+" has been bound to the value of the procedure "*", the result is the product of the two operands.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R5RS resolves this confusion by specifying three procedures that return environments and providing a procedure `eval` that takes an s-expression and an environment and evaluates the expression in the environment provided.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] 6.5) R6RS extends this by providing a procedure called `environment` by which the programmer can specify exactly which objects to import into the evaluation environment.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] `interaction-environment` is the interpreter's global environment.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In most dialects of Lisp including Common Lisp, by convention the value `NIL` evaluates to the value false in a Boolean expression.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, since the IEEE standard in 1991, all values except `#f`, including `NIL`'s equivalent in Scheme which is written as `'()`, evaluate to the value true in a Boolean expression.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Where the constant representing the Boolean value of true is `T` in most Lisps, in Scheme it is `#t`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme the primitive datatypes are disjoint.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Only one of the following predicates can be true of any Scheme object: `boolean?`, `pair?`, `symbol?`, `number?`, `char?`, `string?`, `vector?`, `port?`, `procedure?`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Within the numerical datatype, by contrast, the numerical values overlap.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For example, an integer value satisfies all of the `integer?`, `rational?`, `real?`, `complex?` and `number?` predicates at the same time.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Type dependent equivalence operations also exist in Scheme: `string=?` and `string-ci=?` compare two strings (the latter performs a case-independent comparison); `char=?` and `char-ci=?` compare characters; `=` compares numbers.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Up to the R5RS standard, the standard comment in Scheme was a semicolon, which makes the rest of the line invisible to Scheme.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme's input and output is based on the *port* datatype.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] (R5RS sec 6.6) R5RS defines two default ports, accessible with the procedures `current-input-port` and `current-output-port`, which correspond to the Unix notions of standard input and standard output.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most implementations also provide `current-error-port`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Redirection of input and standard output is supported in the standard, by standard procedures such as `with-input-from-file` and `with-output-to-file`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Most implementations provide string ports with similar redirection capabilities, enabling many normal input-output operations to be performed on string buffers instead of files, using procedures described in SRFI 6.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard specifies much more sophisticated and capable port procedures and many new types of port.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following examples are written in strict R5RS Scheme.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Example 5: As 2, but with using call-with-output-file to send output to a file.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Similar procedures are provided for input.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R5RS Scheme provides the predicates `input-port?` and `output-port?`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For character input and output, `write-char`, `read-char`, `peek-char` and `char-ready?` are provided.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For writing and reading Scheme expressions, Scheme provides `read` and `write`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] On a read operation, the result returned is the end-of-file object if the input port has reached the end of the file, and this can be tested using the predicate `eof-object?`.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] With the standard, SRFI 28 also defines a basic formatting procedure resembling Common Lisp's `format` function, after which it is named.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, procedures are bound to variables.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] At R5RS the language standard formally mandated that programs may change the variable bindings of built-in procedures, effectively redefining them.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In R6RS every binding, including the standard ones, belongs to some library, and all exported bindings are immutable.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] (R6RS sec 7.1) Because of this, redefinition of standard procedures by mutation is forbidden.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Instead, it is possible to import a different procedure under the name of a standard one, which in effect is similar to redefinition.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In Standard Scheme, procedures that convert from one datatype to another contain the character string "->" in their name, predicates end with a "?", and procedures that change the value of already-allocated data end with a "!".
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] These conventions are often followed by Scheme programmers.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In formal contexts such as Scheme standards, the word "procedure" is used in preference to "function" to refer to a lambda expression or primitive procedure.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In normal usage, the words "procedure" and "function" are used interchangeably.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Procedure application is sometimes referred to formally as *combination*.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] As in other Lisps, the term "thunk" is used in Scheme to refer to a procedure with no arguments.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The term "proper tail recursion" refers to the property of all Scheme implementations, that they perform tail-call optimization so as to support an indefinite number of active tail calls.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The language is formally defined in the standards R5RS (1998), R6RS (2007), and R7RS (2013).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] They describe standard "forms": keywords and accompanying syntax, which provide the control structure of the language, and standard procedures which perform common tasks.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] This table describes the standard forms in Scheme.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Some forms appear in more than one row because they cannot easily be classified into a single function in the language.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Forms marked "L" in this table are classed as derived "library" forms in the standard and are often implemented as macros using more fundamental forms in practice, making the task of implementation much easier than in other languages.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] While `begin` is defined as a library syntax in R5RS, the expander must know about it to achieve the splicing function.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In R6RS it is no longer a library syntax.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The following two tables describe the standard procedures in R5RS Scheme.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] R6RS is far more extensive and a summary of this type would not be practical.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Some procedures appear in more than one row because they cannot easily be classified into a single function in the language.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] String and character procedures that contain "-ci" in their names perform case-independent comparisons between their arguments: upper case and lower case versions of the same character are taken to be equal.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Implementations of - and / that take more than two arguments are defined but left optional at R5RS.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Because of Scheme's minimalism, many common procedures and syntactic forms are not defined by the standard.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] In order to keep the core language small but facilitate standardization of extensions, the Scheme community has a "Scheme Request for Implementation" (SRFI) process by which extension libraries are defined through careful discussion of extension proposals.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Many of the SRFIs are supported by all or most Scheme implementations.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The elegant, minimalist design has made Scheme a popular target for language designers, hobbyists, and educators, and because of its small size, that of a typical interpreter, it is also a popular choice for embedded systems and scripting.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard specifies a much broader language, in an attempt to broaden its appeal to programmers.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Almost all implementations provide a traditional Lisp-style read–eval–print loop for development and debugging.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Many also compile Scheme programs to executable binary.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Support for embedding Scheme code in programs written in other languages is also common, as the relative simplicity of Scheme implementations makes it a popular choice for adding scripting capabilities to larger systems developed in languages such as C.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The Gambit, Chicken, and Bigloo Scheme interpreters compile Scheme to C, which makes embedding far easier.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Further, Bigloo's compiler can be configured to generate bytecode for the Java virtual machine (JVM), and has an experimental bytecode generator for .NET.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Some implementations support added features.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For example, Kawa and JScheme provide integration with Java classes, and the Scheme to C compilers often make it easy to use external libraries written in C, up to allowing the embedding of C code in the Scheme source code.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Another example is Pvts, which offers a set of visual tools that support Scheme learning.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is widely used by several schools; in particular, several introductory computer science courses use Scheme in conjunction with the textbook *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* (SICP).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] For the past 12 years, PLT has run the ProgramByDesign (formerly TeachScheme!) project, which has exposed close to 600 high school teachers and thousands of high school students to rudimentary Scheme programming.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] MIT's old introductory programming class 6.001 was taught in Scheme, Although 6.001 has been replaced by more modern courses, SICP continues to be taught at MIT.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Likewise, the introductory class at UC Berkeley, CS 61A, was until 2011 taught entirely in Scheme, save minor diversions into Logo to demonstrate dynamic scope.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Today, like MIT, Berkeley has replaced the syllabus with a more modern version that is primarily taught in Python 3, but the current syllabus is still based on the old curriculum, and parts of the class are still taught in Scheme.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The textbook *How to Design Programs* is used by some institutes of higher education for their introductory computer science courses.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Worcester Polytechnic Institute uses Scheme exclusively for its introductory course Introduction to Program Design (CS1101).
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology uses Scheme in its more advanced Programming Language Concepts course.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Brandeis University's core course, Structure and Interpretations of Computer Programs (COSI121b), is also taught exclusively in Scheme by theoretical computer scientist Harry Mairson.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] Indiana University's introductory class, C211, is taught entirely in Scheme.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] A self-paced version of the course, CS 61AS, continues to use Scheme.
[src:gambit-scheme/scheme-programming-language] The introductory computer science courses at Yale and Grinnell College are also taught in Scheme.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] In computer programming, **self-hosting** is the use of a program as part of the toolchain or operating system that produces new versions of that same program—for example, a compiler that can compile its own source code.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Self-hosting software is commonplace on personal computers and larger systems.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Other programs that are typically self-hosting include kernels, assemblers, command-line interpreters and revision control software.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] An operating system is self-hosted when the toolchain to build the operating system runs on that same operating system.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] For example, Windows can be built on a computer running Windows.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Before a system can become self-hosted, another system is needed to develop it until it reaches a stage where self-hosting is possible.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] When developing for a new computer or operating system, a system to run the development software is needed, but development software used to write and build the operating system is also necessary.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] This is called a bootstrapping problem or, more generically, a chicken or the egg dilemma.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] A solution to this problem is the cross compiler (or cross assembler when working with assembly language).
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] A cross compiler allows source code on one platform to be compiled for a different machine or operating system, making it possible to create an operating system for a machine for which a self-hosting compiler does not yet exist.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Once written, software can be deployed to the target system using means such as an EPROM, floppy diskette, flash memory (such as a USB thumb drive), or JTAG device.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] This is similar to the method used to write software for gaming consoles or for handheld devices like cellular phones or tablets, which do not host their own development tools.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Once the system is mature enough to compile its own code, the cross-development dependency ends.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] At this point, an operating system is said to be self-hosted.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Software development using compiler or interpreters can also be self hosted when the compiler is capable of compiling itself.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Since self-hosted compilers suffer from the same bootstrap problems as operating systems, a compiler for a new programming language needs to be written in an existing language.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] So the developer may use something like assembly language, C/C++, or even a scripting language like Python or Lua to build the first version of the compiler.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Once the language is mature enough, development of the compiler can shift to the compiler's native language, allowing the compiler to build itself.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Note that some of these points assume that the language runtime is also written in the same language.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] The first self-hosting compiler (excluding assemblers) was written for Lisp by Hart and Levin at MIT in 1962.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] They wrote a Lisp compiler in Lisp, testing it inside an existing Lisp Interpreter.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Once they had improved the compiler to the point where it could compile its own source code, it was self-hosting.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] This technique is usually only practicable when an interpreter already exists for the very same language that is to be compiled; though possible, it is extremely uncommon to humanly compile a compiler with itself.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] The concept borrows directly from and is an example of the broader notion of running a program on itself as input, used also in various proofs in theoretical computer science, such as the proof that the halting problem is undecidable.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Ken Thompson started development on Unix in 1968 by writing and compiling programs on the GE-635 and carrying them over to the PDP-7 for testing.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] After the initial Unix kernel, a command interpreter, an editor, an assembler, and a few utilities were completed, the Unix operating system was self-hosting – programs could be written and tested on the PDP-7 itself.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Douglas McIlroy wrote TMG (a compiler-compiler) in TMG on a piece of paper and "decided to give his piece of paper to his piece of paper", doing the computation himself, thus compiling a TMG compiler into assembly, which he typed up and assembled on Ken Thompson's PDP-7.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Development of the GNU system relies largely on GCC (the GNU Compiler Collection) and GNU Emacs (a popular editor), making possible the self contained, maintained and sustained development of free software for the GNU Project.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] Many programming languages have self-hosted implementations: compilers that are both in and for the same language.
[src:gambit-scheme/self-hosting-compilers] An approach is bootstrapping, where a core version of the language is initially implemented using another high-level language, assembler, or even machine language; the resulting compiler is then used to start building successive expanded versions of itself.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] In computer science, a **tail call** is a subroutine call performed as the final action of a procedure.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] If the target of a tail is the same subroutine, the subroutine is said to be **tail recursive**, which is a special case of direct recursion.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] **Tail recursion** (or **tail-end recursion**) is particularly useful, and is often easy to optimize in implementations.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Tail calls can be implemented without adding a new stack frame to the call stack.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Most of the frame of the current procedure is no longer needed, and can be replaced by the frame of the tail call, modified as appropriate (similar to overlay for processes, but for function calls).
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The program can then jump to the called subroutine.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Producing such code instead of a standard call sequence is called **tail-call elimination** or **tail-call optimization**.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Tail-call elimination allows procedure calls in tail position to be implemented as efficiently as goto statements, thus allowing efficient structured programming.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Not all programming languages require tail-call elimination.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] However, in functional programming languages, tail-call elimination is often guaranteed by the language standard, allowing tail recursion to use a similar amount of memory as an equivalent loop.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The special case of tail-recursive calls, when a function calls itself, may be more amenable to call elimination than general tail calls.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] When the language semantics do not explicitly support general tail calls, a compiler can often still optimize **sibling calls**, or tail calls to functions which take and return the same types as the caller.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] When a function is called, the computer must "remember" the place it was called from, the *return address*, so that it can return to that location with the result once the call is complete.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Typically, this information is saved on the call stack, a list of return locations in the order that the call locations were reached.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] In addition, compilers allocate memory for local variables of the called function and push register content (if any and/or relevant) onto the stack.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Typically, it is done by allocating a stack frame including saved registers, space allocated for non-register local variables, return address and call parameters (unless they are passed in registers).
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This, however, leads to complete loss of the caller's stack frame, which is sometimes considered as a hindrance in debugging.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The tail call doesn't have to appear lexically after all other statements in the source code; it is only important that the calling function return immediately after the tail call, returning the tail call's result if any, since the calling function is bypassed when the optimization is performed.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] For non-recursive function calls, this is usually an optimization that saves only a little time and space, since there are not that many different functions available to call.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] When dealing with recursive or mutually recursive functions where recursion happens through tail calls, however, the stack space and the number of returns saved can grow to be very significant, since a function can call itself, directly or indirectly, creating a new call stack frame each time.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Tail-call elimination often reduces asymptotic stack space requirements from linear, or O(n), to constant, or O(1).
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Tail-call elimination is thus required by the standard definitions of some programming languages, such as Scheme, and languages in the ML family among others.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The Scheme language definition formalizes the intuitive notion of tail position exactly, by specifying which syntactic forms allow having results in tail context.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Implementations allowing an unlimited number of tail calls to be active at the same moment, thanks to tail-call elimination, can also be called 'properly tail recursive'.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Besides space and execution efficiency, tail-call elimination is important in the functional programming idiom known as continuation-passing style (CPS), which would otherwise quickly run out of stack space.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] A tail call can be located just before the syntactical end of a function.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Here, both `a(data)` and `b(data)` are calls, but `b` is the last thing the procedure executes before returning and is thus in tail position.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Here, both calls to `b` and `c` are in tail position.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This is because each of them lies in the end of if-branch respectively, even though the first one is not syntactically at the end of `bar`'s body.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The call to `a(data)` is in tail position in `foo2`, but it is **not** in tail position either in `foo1` or in `foo3`, because control must return to the caller to allow it to inspect or modify the return value before returning it.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This is not written in a tail-recursive style, because the multiplication function ("*") is in the tail position.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This program assumes applicative-order evaluation.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The inner procedure `fact-iter` calls itself *last* in the control flow.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This reorganization saves space because no state except for the calling function's address needs to be saved, either on the stack or on the heap, and the call stack frame for `fact-iter` is reused for the intermediate results storage.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This also means that the programmer need not worry about running out of stack or heap space for extremely deep recursions.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] In typical implementations, the tail-recursive variant will be substantially faster than the other variant, but only by a constant factor.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Some programmers working in functional languages will rewrite recursive code to be tail recursive so they can take advantage of this feature.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This often requires addition of an "accumulator" argument (`product` in the above example) to the function.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Thus in tail-recursive translation such a call is transformed into first creating a new list node and setting its `first` field, and *then* making the tail call with the pointer to the node's `rest` field as argument, to be filled recursively.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The same effect is achieved when the recursion is *guarded* under a lazily evaluated data constructor, which is automatically achieved in lazy programming languages like Haskell.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] In this form the function is not tail recursive, because control returns to the caller after the recursive call duplicates the rest of the input list.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Even if it were to allocate the *head* node before duplicating the rest, it would still need to plug in the result of the recursive call into the `next` field *after* the call.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] So the function is *almost* tail recursive.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Warren's method pushes the responsibility of filling the `next` field into the recursive call itself, which thus becomes tail call.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The callee now appends to the end of the growing list, rather than have the caller prepend to the beginning of the returned list.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The work is now done on the way *forward* from the list's start, *before* the recursive call which then proceeds further, instead of *backward* from the list's end, *after* the recursive call has returned its result.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] It is thus similar to the accumulating parameter technique, turning a recursive computation into an iterative one.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Characteristically for this technique, a parent frame is created on the execution call stack, which the tail-recursive callee can reuse as its own call frame if the tail-call optimization is present.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] In a paper delivered to the ACM conference in Seattle in 1977, Guy L.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Steele summarized the debate over the GOTO and structured programming, and observed that procedure calls in the tail position of a procedure can be best treated as a direct transfer of control to the called procedure, typically eliminating unnecessary stack manipulation operations.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Since such "tail calls" are very common in Lisp, a language where procedure calls are ubiquitous, this form of optimization considerably reduces the cost of a procedure call compared to other implementations.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Steele argued that poorly-implemented procedure calls had led to an artificial perception that the GOTO was cheap compared to the procedure call.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Steele cited evidence that well-optimized numerical algorithms in Lisp could execute faster than code produced by then-available commercial Fortran compilers because the cost of a procedure call in Lisp was much lower.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] In Scheme, a Lisp dialect developed by Steele with Gerald Jay Sussman, tail-call elimination is guaranteed to be implemented in any interpreter.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Tail recursion is important to some high-level languages, especially functional and logic languages and members of the Lisp family.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] In these languages, tail recursion is the most commonly used way (and sometimes the only way available) of implementing iteration.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The language specification of Scheme requires that tail calls are to be optimized so as not to grow the stack.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] For these cases, optimizing tail recursion remains trivial, but general tail-call optimization may be harder to implement efficiently.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] For example, in the Java virtual machine (JVM), tail-recursive calls can be eliminated (as this reuses the existing call stack), but general tail calls cannot be (as this changes the call stack).
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] As a result, functional languages such as Scala that target the JVM can efficiently implement direct tail recursion, but not mutual tail recursion.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The GCC, LLVM/Clang, and Intel compiler suites perform tail-call optimization for C and other languages at higher optimization levels or when the `-foptimize-sibling-calls` option is passed.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Various implementation methods are available.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Tail calls are often optimized by interpreters and compilers of functional programming and logic programming languages to more efficient forms of iteration.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] For example, Scheme programmers commonly express while loops as calls to procedures in tail position and rely on the Scheme compiler or interpreter to substitute the tail calls with more efficient jump instructions.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] For compilers generating assembly directly, tail-call elimination is easy: it suffices to replace a call opcode with a jump one, after fixing parameters on the stack.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] After subroutine `A` completes, it will then return directly to the return address of `foo`, omitting the unnecessary `ret` statement.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Typically, the subroutines being called need to be supplied with parameters.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] The generated code thus needs to make sure that the call frame for A is properly set up before jumping to the tail-called subroutine.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] For instance, on platforms where the call stack does not just contain the return address, but also the parameters for the subroutine, the compiler may need to emit instructions to adjust the call stack.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This code is more efficient both in terms of execution speed and use of stack space.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] From a compiler's perspective, a pure tail call is most visible in recursive functions.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] A tail-call optimizer recognizes that the current stack frame is no longer needed after the call.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This optimized code is physically identical to an imperative `while` loop, executing with strictly bounded memory and maximal speed.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] In bare-metal environments and formal automata theory, a pure tail call is defined primarily by its space complexity: **a pure tail call occurs when the stack space is strictly bounded during recursion**.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] By guaranteeing that the stack pointer does not grow proportionally to the recursion depth, tail calls allow infinitely deep recursive evaluation to operate within strict physical memory constraints (such as a microkernel or a boot sector).
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This physically transforms the call stack into a bounded state machine.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] A tail call without recursion is physically equivalent to an assembly `JMP` instruction.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This property makes the tail call a fundamental primitive for implementing high-performance coroutines.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] By replacing the traditional `CALL` and `RET` cycle with a direct jump to the next state, an execution engine can "hand off" control between different functional units in constant stack space.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This mechanism is central to Continuation-passing style, where the program never returns, but instead performs a sequence of tail calls to transition between cooperative states.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Since many Scheme compilers use C as an intermediate target code, the tail recursion must be encoded in C without growing the stack, even if the C compiler does not optimize tail calls.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Many implementations achieve this by using a device known as a trampoline, a piece of code that repeatedly calls functions.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] All functions are entered via the trampoline.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] This ensures that the C stack does not grow and iteration can continue indefinitely.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] It is possible to implement trampolines using higher-order functions in languages that support them, such as Groovy, Visual Basic .NET and C#.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] When the stack reaches its maximum permitted size, objects on the stack are garbage-collected using the Cheney algorithm by moving all live data into a separate heap.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Following this, the stack is unwound ("popped") and the program resumes from the state saved just before the garbage collection.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] Baker says "Appel's method avoids making a large number of small trampoline bounces by occasionally jumping off the Empire State Building." The garbage collection ensures that mutual tail recursion can continue indefinitely.
[src:gambit-scheme/tail-call] However, this approach requires that no C function call ever returns, since there is no guarantee that its caller's stack frame still exists; therefore, it involves a much more dramatic internal rewriting of the program code: continuation-passing style.
